docs.abstract: I couldn’t understand why I was able to move on from my traumatic experiences until I joined a PTSD study.
docs.snippet: I couldn’t understand why I was able to move on from my traumatic experiences until I joined a PTSD study.
docs.lead_paragraph: A few years ago, my husband, Chris, who survived four deployments to Iraq and Afghanistan, was killed by an avalanche in Colorado. I am an Army veteran who was deployed to combat zones twice, in 2005 and 2008, without any serious lingering psychological ramifications. But I thought my husband’s death, that New Year’s Eve day, would be the final trigger for post-traumatic stress disorder; it would be what sent me over the edge.

headline.main: I’m a Veteran Without PTSD. I Used to Think Something Was Wrong With Me.
